{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493289"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:04:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:04:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1277"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1277"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.04,0.2,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1277"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98609"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1277"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1277"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81008"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"141"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3213"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33443"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43068"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98609"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman from a nursing home undergoes a routine DEXA scan for bone mineral density. Her T-score is -3.0. Her blood tests are within normal range, including calcium, parathyroid hormone, and vitamin D levels. Her medical history includes oesophageal stricture, breast cancer (treated with lumpectomy and radiotherapy), atrial fibrillation, fractured left neck of femur, and glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next test before commencing therapy for osteoporosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further tests required","C-telopeptide of type 1 collagen (CTX)","Bone-specific alkaline phosphatase (bsALP)","Osteocalcin","Procollagen type 1 N propeptide (P1NP)"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further tests required\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer because the patient\u0027s T-score of -3.0 confirms osteoporosis, and immediate treatment can be initiated. In patients with a T-score \u2264 -2.5, pharmacological therapy for osteoporosis is warranted without the need for additional testing, provided there is no suspicion of secondary causes. Secondary causes should be suspected if Z-scores are \u2264-2.0. This suggests significant reduction in bone density compared to the average bone density of healthy people of the same age and sex. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf note, it is appropriate to commence pharmacological therapy for osteoporosis for the following patients:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThose with a minimal trauma hip or vertebral fracture* \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E*Vertebral fracture defined as loss of height \u226520%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThose with minimal trauma at another site and T-score \u2264 -1.5\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThose with T-score \u2264 -2.5\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThose with a high 10-year risk of fracture\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUse validated risk calculators including FRAX and Garvan \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucocorticoid-induced osteopenia \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDefined as \u22657.5mg prednisolone dose equivalent for \u22653 months and T-score \u2264 -1.5\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe choice of anti-osteoporosis medication is varied and dependent on the patient\u0027s profile including comorbidities, life expectancy, adherence to proposed regimen. However, baseline calcium and vitamin D levels are typically adequate, unless there is clinical suspicion of an underlying pathology for secondary osteoporosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC-terminal telopeptide of type 1 collagen (CTX)\u003C/strong\u003E is a marker of bone turnover in blood. This is useful to monitor the effects of treatment and can be useful to assess for adherence to therapy. It plays no role in diagnosis of osteoporosis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone-specific alkaline phosphatase (bsALP) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a marker of bone formation, being an enzyme produced predominantly by osteoblasts. It can be elevated in Paget\u0027s disease which results in dysfunctional bone remodeling, and also during fracture healing. It should only be requested if alkaline phosphatase is consistently elevated and other causes like liver disease have been excluded, but is not essential nor required to inform treatment decisions for osteoporosis treatment like in this case  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteocalcin \u003C/strong\u003Eis produced by osteoblasts and may be used as a marker for bone formation. It is correlated with higher bone mineral density and can be used to measure the effectiveness of treatment. However, it is not necessary prior to starting pharmacological therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcollagen type 1 N propeptide (P1NP) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a marker of bone formation and may be elevated in response to increased bone formation or in pathologies such as infection. Once again it has some clinical value in following treatment efficacy or when assessing for other differentials but is not necessary prior to starting pharmacological therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients without suspected secondary osteoporosis, pharmacological therapy may be started immediately following measurement of Vitamin D and Calcium levels.","A number of biomarkers may be used to track treatment of osteoporosis."],"references":["E. \u00a0Ensrud K, J. \u00a0Crandall C. Osteoporosis. Annals of Internal Medicine [Internet]. 2017 Aug 1 [cited 2021 Jul 12]; Available from: https://www-acpjournals-org.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/doi/abs/10.7326/AITC201708010"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81008"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1277"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81008"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-15T18:41:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-15T18:42:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1277"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98609"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ta